4-Create the following hierarchy under your home directory:

[devops@localhost ~]$ mkdir dir1

[devops@localhost ~]$ cd dir1

[devops@localhost dir1]$ mkdir dir11 dir12

[devops@localhost dir1]$ cd dir11
[devops@localhost dir11]$ touch file1

[devops@localhost ~]$ mkdir doc
[devops@localhost ~]$ cd doc
[devops@localhost doc]$ touch mycv


a. Remove dir11 in one-step
[devops@localhost doc]$ cd ..

[devops@localhost ~]$ rm -r  dir1/dir11

b. Then remove dir12 using rmdir â€“p command.

[devops@localhost ~]$ rmdir -p  dir1/dir12

c. The output of the command pwd was /home/user. Write the absolute
and relative path for the file mycv

[devops@localhost /]$ cd /home/devops/doc     

[devops@localhost doc]$ cd
[devops@localhost ~]$ cd doc

5. Copy the /etc/passwd file to your home directory making its name is mypasswd.

[devops@localhost doc]$ cd ~
[devops@localhost ~]$ cp /etc/passwd mypasswd


6. Rename this new file to be oldpasswd.

[devops@localhost ~]$ mv mypasswd oldpasswd

7. You are in /usr/bin, list four ways to go to your home directory
[devops@localhost ~]$ cd /usr/bin
[devops@localhost bin]$ cd
[devops@localhost ~]$ cd /usr/bin
[devops@localhost bin]$ cd ~
[devops@localhost ~]$ cd /usr/bin
[devops@localhost bin]$ cd /home/devops
[devops@localhost ~]$ cd /usr/bin
[devops@localhost bin]$ cd $home
[devops@localhost ~]$ 

8. List Linux commands in /usr/bin that start with letter w
[devops@localhost ~]$ ls /usr/bin/w*


9. Display the first 4 lines of /etc/passwd

[devops@localhost ~]$ head -n4 /etc/passwd

10. Display the last 7 lines of /etc/passwd

[devops@localhost ~]$ tail -n7 /etc/passwd

11. Display the man pages of passwd the command and the file sequentially in one command.
[devops@localhost ~]$ man 1 5 passwd

12. Display the man page of the passwd file.

[devops@localhost ~]$ man 5 passwd

13. Display a list of all the commands that contain the keyword passwd in their man page.
[devops@localhost ~]$ man -k passwd


